<subSubSection box="[192,1177,890,916]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="34.[192,1177,890,916]" box="[192,1177,890,916]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,316,890,916]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The completely yellow dorsum will distinguish these beetles from congeners.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="33" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="34.[192,1441,931,1127]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,338,931,957]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[346,389,932,958]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Size</emphasis>
. Length 8.0 mm; width 2.0 mm. 
<emphasis box="[770,827,932,957]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Form</emphasis>
. As in 
<figureCitation box="[910,1003,932,958]" captionStart="Figures 110–113" captionStartId="68.[192,279,1859,1885]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1827]" captionTargetId="figure-11@68.[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetPageId="68" captionText="Figures 110–113. Habitus of Axina species. 110) Axina vista. 111) A. nigrifrons. 112) A. ochra. 113) A. analis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565035" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565035/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Fig. 112</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis box="[1015,1076,932,958]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Color</emphasis>
. Yellow, except antennae, tibiae, and tarsi black. 
<emphasis box="[366,425,965,991]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Head</emphasis>
. Cranium finely punctate, frons about as wide as length of antennal pedicel; EW/FW 45/15. 
<emphasis box="[192,270,999,1025]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Thorax</emphasis>
. Pronotum finely punctate, with 2 tumescences, concave at middle; PW/PL 95/120; elytra, asetiferous punctures substriate, punctures extend to elytron middle, width of interstitial spaces variable; EL/EW 360/65. 
<emphasis box="[192,298,1067,1093]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[434,515,1067,1093]" captionStart="Figures 33–36" captionStartId="49.[192,279,645,671]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,614]" captionTargetId="figure-11@49.[192,1440,213,614]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figures 33–36. Aedeagi. 33) Axina polycaula. 34) A. ochra. 35) A. rio. 36) A. spina." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4564979" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4564979/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
), phallobasic lobes very short, narrowly separated; margin of phallic plates serrate, phallic apex extended; phallobasic apodeme abbreviated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[192,1440,1142,1202]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,310,1142,1168]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Variation.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[316,359,1143,1169]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Size</emphasis>
. Length 7.0–8.0 mm; width 1.5–2.0 mm. Other than body size, the available specimens are quite homogeneous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[192,1190,1218,1245]" box="[192,1190,1218,1245]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,376,1218,1244]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Natural history.</emphasis>
Specimens were collected in 
<collectingCountry box="[702,780,1218,1244]" name="Bolivia" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
during October, at 430 and 
<quantity box="[1094,1186,1218,1245]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.025" pageId="34" pageNumber="33" unit="m" value="1025.0">1,025 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[192,983,1260,1287]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="34.[192,983,1260,1287]" box="[192,983,1260,1287]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,339,1260,1286]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Distribution</emphasis>
(for map see 
<figureCitation box="[490,567,1260,1286]" captionStart="Figure 71" captionStartId="56.[194,270,1867,1893]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-11@56.[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="Figure 71. Distribution map for Axina species: A. luzia, A. munda, A. minas, A. pallidioccabus, A. picta, A. pollex, A. polycaula, A. proxima, A. rio, A. villa, A. vista, A. nigrifrons, A. ochra." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565003" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565003/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
). This species is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[897,979,1260,1286]" name="Bolivia" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="33" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="34.[192,1440,1302,1362]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,1302,1328]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2020" box="[565,624,1302,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ochra">
<emphasis box="[565,624,1302,1328]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">ochra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a Greek name derived from 
<emphasis box="[984,1054,1302,1328]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">ochros</emphasis>
(= pale yellow). I refer to the predominant color of these beetles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[688,944,1397,1426]" box="[688,944,1397,1426]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[688,944,1397,1426]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">analis species group</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[192,1439,1441,1502]" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">
The female members of this group are characterized by showing a trilobed pygidium. There are six species in this group whose geographical distribution involves 
<collectingCountry box="[727,808,1475,1501]" name="Bolivia" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[818,886,1475,1501]" name="Brazil" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[896,1011,1475,1501]" name="Argentina" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1070,1174,1476,1502]" name="Paraguay" pageId="34" pageNumber="33">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
